(214, 1, '2015-05-12 19:57:20', '2015-05-12 19:57:20', 'Now that this year is coming to fast close, it’s time to look ahead and prepare for how front-end design trends have grown and changed. We talked to our talented team of engineers and asked them what they believe their top front-end developer trends are for 2015.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>Compatibility </b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>AngularJS, BackboneJS, React are still going strong.</i></h3>\r\nJavascript frameworks - such as <b>AngularJS, Backbone.js </b>and <b>React </b>- have reached a new stability level,  and cross-browser compatibility has developed in such a way that it\'s no longer a risk to implement JS based applications. Before, cross-browser compatibility used to prevent big corporations from adopting those frameworks, as they usually had to support a lot of old browsers. Nowadays, frameworks have better support for multiple browsers (and most of them are still supporting really old ones like IE7, IE8). As a result, they are being used more by big players in the market. That\'s a trend we can see with most of our clients at Avenue Code.\r\n<h2><b>Web Components</b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>libraries agree - components are awesome!</i></h3>\r\nWeb Components will become even more important in 2015 because it will turn front-end development inside out. Web Components greatly simplifies how UI components are developed, by favoring reuse and sharing component-specific knowledge. It will trend because of the increasing focus on the "web componentizing" approach advocated by libraries such as <b>React</b>, which forces the developer to define the web application as a tree of fully-featured components. Besides that, there has been a big progress leap with the specification of Web Components, which is being widely promoted by libraries such as <b>Polymer </b>and <b>X-Tags</b>.\r\n\r\nWeb Components are awesome because it directly attacks the current number of development challenges - such as code repetition, bad cohesion, poor coupling, inability to reuse the component in different contexts, and lack of testing and certification by the community, which essentially forces one to reinvent the wheel each time. Web Components will provide a productivity boom for the front-end development world.\r\n<h2><b><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mobile-1.png">\r\n</a><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mobile-1.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-562 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mobile-1-212x300.png" alt="" width="212" height="300" /></a></b><b></b></h2>\r\n<h2><b>Mobile-first Design</b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>Consumers can be found on their phones, we must adjust accordingly!</i></h3>\r\nMobile-first design should lead development methods due to responsive design techniques maturedness. Mobile device usage has exploded, and creative teams should explore newer features (e.g. geolocation, touch) in order to define unique experiences like real-time trackers, local-based content, etc.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2><b><img class="alignleft wp-image-563 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Untitled-design-200x300.png" alt="Untitled design" width="200" height="300" />User Experience</b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>Natural design will still be king.</i></h3>\r\nNext year’s UX trends will take advantage of some natural (intuitive) gestures provided by the mobile devices themselves (especially swiping and scrolling). As a direct result, there should be more usage of content in a single page instead of the user having to click on multiple links to find what he or she is looking for.\r\n\r\nThe cool thing about these three trends is that they converge to provide a faster, more intuitive, and cleaner web experience that stays consistent regardless of when a user switches from one device to another. Lastly, community will continue to be a large part of front-end design, specifically with web components.\r\nLooks like the theme for 2015 is beautifully simple and stable front-end design and development. We aim to do more with less...looks like everyone else will too in the new year.', 'Front-end Design Trends for 2015', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '209-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:57:20', '2015-05-12 19:57:20', '', 209, 'http://revamp.avenuecode.com/209-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
