(220, 1, '2015-05-12 19:58:00', '2015-05-12 19:58:00', 'This was a tasting menu kind of trip, a day or two in selected cities in Northern Europe. It was my first time, so I just wanted to feel the region in order to go back and spend more time on the favorite ones.\r\n\r\nPictures speak better than words, and one of my favorite pastime activities during travel is photography. So here is my trip in a picturesque and chronological order.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/01.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-416" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/01.png" alt="Copenhagen, DK" width="638" height="424" /></a>\r\n\r\nCopenhagen, DK. A little sleepy town, that comes to life only on Friday night between 6-7:30 pm. I wasn’t there to witness that crazy party. If you ever find yourself in there with nothing to do, ask for directions to Christiania Island, even for us non-smokers, this place is quite interesting to see. They don’t let you take pictures, so you’ll just have to see for yourself.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/02.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-417" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/02.png" alt="Viking Line crossing the Baltic from Stockholm to Helsinki" width="677" height="450" /></a>\r\n\r\nOn the Viking Line crossing the Baltic from Stockholm to Helsinki. This sky, beats the Da Vinci Sky in my opinion.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/03.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-418" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/03.png" alt="Silence Church in Helsinki" width="621" height="413" /></a>\r\n\r\nSilence Church in Helsinki. I think the design was inspired by a wine bottle’s cork. Helsinki reminded me of the eastern block, although they’ve never been a part of the Soviet Union, even with all the Russian arm-twisting. Go Fenland!! Your resilience can only be rivaled by you vodka.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/04.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-419" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/04.png" alt="04" width="638" height="424" /></a>\r\n\r\nOld Town Tallinn, Estonia.   I took this picture from a hang glider. No, seriously, have I ever exaggerated before?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/05.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-420" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/05.png" alt="05" width="597" height="750" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Three Sisters Hotel in Old Tallinn, I had the room on the top left. This is the oldest building I’ve ever spent the night in, more than 700 years old.  Looking forward to breaking this record by sneaking a bed into the Pyramids.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/06.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-422" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/06.png" alt="Stockholm" width="898" height="597" /></a>\r\n\r\nGoodbye Nordic! last day, Stockholm.', 'My Trip to Northern Europe', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '212-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:58:00', '2015-05-12 19:58:00', '', 212, 'http://revamp.avenuecode.com/212-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(221, 1, '2014-09-23 21:44:27', '2014-09-23 21:44:27', 'It has been a while since web applications first began taking a major role in software development. Beginning as basic static pages with no interactions at all, web applications have since developed into highly complex, rich, and interactive digital organisms. Among this soup of new technologies, components and enhancements that facilitated this development, one of them stands out as a key factor making it all possible.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI still remember the days when Javascript was mainly used for client-side validations.  Remember how impressed we were?  Wow!  We could validate forms without wasting bandwidth with useless requests to the server!  Who would have imagined that only a few years later javascript could be used to run full applications on your browser?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBut as breakneck as this development has been, not everything has kept up at the same pace. It’s still common to come across some messy and poorly conceived/modularized Javascript code.  Poor testing practices are often at the root of this.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTesting -- I’m not talking about manually clicking randomly across your page looking for some weird behavior. Unit tests, navigation tests, integration tests, automated tests -- there’s a wide array of testing practices available so that product quality and efficiency can be ensured.  These tests that are typically employed to ensure the backend runs smoothly can also be applied to your front-end code.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-411 size-full" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/tests.png" alt="" width="494" height="330" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><b>Why testing?</b></h2>\r\nShort answer: to make sure it works.  Although we can rarely test our code to such an extent that it is guaranteed fail-proof, we can at least use testing to ascertain how a program will behave for certain given (expected) scenarios.  That’s already a LOT as you are cutting failure possibilities to edge cases (which you will create tests for in case they show up).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFront-end applications are complex; they have models, events, data handling and a bunch of other variables that can easily get out of hand if you don’t assure that functions are actually constrained to do what you have intended for them do.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTesting your code also provides a good way to determine how abstract and modularized your program is. The simple act of making code testable ensures that you are organizing your code with some kind of modularity. Try it. You’ll be thanking yourself in the future.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-406" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/yes-we-can.gif" alt="yes-we-can" width="800" height="300" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><b>So... How?</b></h2>\r\nHopefully this introduction convinced you of the importance of these tests. Now let’s talk about how they can actually be done. To make it less overwhelming I will split this into a series of posts that will walk you through the different processes. On this first post, I will explain each layer of our stack.  The following posts will elaborate on the variety of existing options and provide some tips on how to select the best one for your needs.\r\n<h2><b>A Typical Front-end Test Stack </b></h2>\r\n<h3><b>Test Framework</b></h3>\r\nThis component is responsible for making sure your tests will be run correctly. It does all the needed setup, loads dependencies, describes test suites, runs test cases and outputs results.\r\n<h3><b>Assertion Libraries</b></h3>\r\nThis provides the expectation language you will need to assert your test cases. This might seem simple to the point of triviality to you (and in most cases it actually is) but there are some cool and powerful extensions to these libraries that can sometimes be exactly what you need to best that “untestable” code.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-432" style="width: 540px !important;" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/qunit.png" alt="qunit" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Mocking Tools</b></h3>\r\nWhile it’s important to make everything work together, it’s also important to make sure every component can work properly when independently deployed. That’s why we need options to mock data or requests and simulate communication with other parties and assert our code behaves to all possible situations. The best part of this is that we can even simulate communication failures!\r\n<h3><b>Browsers / Automated tasks</b></h3>\r\nWe all know how boring it is to keep doing the same tests in different browsers. Why waste our time on these repetitive tasks when we can automate and let our machine do all the work for us?\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-448" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/test-diagram.png" alt="test-diagram" width="552" height="480" /></p>', 'Front-end tests: Yes we can!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'front-end-tests-yes-we-can', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:16:18', '2015-05-18 17:16:18', '', 0, 'http://revamp.avenuecode.com/?p=221', 0, 'post', '', 0) ;
