(222, 1, '2014-09-19 21:43:40', '2014-09-19 21:43:40', 'This is the inaugural posting in a series of articles/tutorials/lessons (Or whatever synonymous term you would like to use!) aimed at illustrating how to design java software using Object Oriented Programming (OOP).  We will be modeling our problems to make them all as simple and palatable as mac &amp; cheese.\r\n\r\nBy the end of this 2-part article, you will understand how a simple software program works, how we design software to solve real-world problems, and something that would be a resume-builder for even the most seasoned professional: How to solve a Rubiks cube!\r\n\r\nUh… what?  Come on… You’re using a tech blog to talk about Rubiks cube?\r\n\r\nYeah!  In all seriousness, a Rubik’s cube is the perfect real-world example of an algorithm in action -- something that we can readily translate to software-ese…\r\n\r\nFirst, what is an algorithm?  An algorithm is an “effective method expressed as a finite list of well-defined instructions for calculating a function.”  In other (non-geek) words: It’s a set of instructions that set the rules for how something can be done.\r\n\r\nWhen you see someone solving a cube, they are in fact following some well-defined instructions, although they could be hyper-genius savants.\r\n\r\n<b>So Let’s get started!</b>\r\n\r\nThe first step is to fully understand what a Rubik’s cube is:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="alignleft" width="524"]<img src="http://www.youcandothecube.com/Themes/rubiks/img/content/solution-stage-one.jpg" alt="How to solve Rubik\'s Cube - Stage 1" width="524" height="1426" /> source: http://www.youcandothecube.com/Themes/rubiks/img/content/solution-stage-one.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNice, huh?  I bet you never thought of a Rubik’s cube like this.\r\n\r\nThis also illustrates one of the crucial parts of our job: <b>Thinking of a good model for our problem.</b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBEFORE starting coding, its imperative that we UNDERSTAND the problem we’re dealing with.  This is where models come in handy.  First let’s talk about what a Rubik’s cube <i>really </i>is, broken down into its characteristic features, which we’ll call <b>PROPERTIES. </b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHere are some of the <b>PROPERTIES </b>of the Rubik’s cube:\r\n\r\n1. It is an object with 26 pieces: 6 center pieces, 12 edge pieces, and 8 corner pieces.\r\n\r\n2. Pieces can have 1 color (center pieces), 2 colors (edges) or 3 colors (corners)\r\n\r\n3. Each piece has a distinct position on the cube\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome of these properties are static:\r\n\r\nWe can’t change the amount of pieces.\r\n\r\nWe can’t change the colors on the pieces.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOthers are dynamic:\r\n\r\nWe can change the position of the pieces!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is good, because solving a Rubik’s cube requires that we move pieces around until all squares of a color are lined up on the same side of the cube.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs mentioned in the infographic, we have 12 possible movements (each of the 6 faces can be moved either clockwise or counterclockwise.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAny action that will <b>MODIFY </b>the object properties -- such as rotating a side of the cube -- we will call <b>METHODS</b>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnd how will we know that the cube is solved?  We will need to <b>CHECK </b>if all the pieces are in the correct place and <b>RETURN</b> an answer.  Anything that <b>RETURNS </b>an answer is called a <b>FUNCTION.  </b>\r\n\r\nTo explain the way this works, we will use a real life analog: simple exchange that goes on between our vision and our brains.  We must visually ascertain that the cube is complete by looking at it.  The visual image we see is then transferred in the form of electrical signals goes to our brains.  This process we might call the ‘check.’  Then the brain receives the image, and evaluates what it is seeing to determine whether the cube is complete or incomplete.  We can think of ‘Complete’ and ‘incomplete’ as values that are ‘returned’by the brain, which, in this analogy, would be the function<b>.  </b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCongratulations!  you just learned 3 crucial concepts in Object Oriented Modeling: <b>Properties, Methods, and Functions!</b>\r\n', 'Object Oriented Programming: Modeling (part 1)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'object-oriented-programming-modeling-part-1', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:16:28', '2015-05-18 17:16:28', '', 0, 'http://revamp.avenuecode.com/?p=222', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(223, 1, '2014-09-16 21:42:53', '2014-09-16 21:42:53', '<div style="color: #222222">This summer I visited Turkey and Greece for 2 weeks. I\'ve always been fascinated with ancient cultural sites and images of waterfront life that countries in the region boast. I had a fascinating experience in Istanbul, looking at how well the old world co-exists with the new. I was quite surprised to see how well everything was maintained.</div> <br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-sunset.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-381" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-sunset-1024x491.jpg" alt="Istanbul sunset" width="600" height="288" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><br><br>\r\n<br><div>The waterfront cafes and districts that proliferate throughout the city are innumerable.</div><br>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Turkey-waterfront.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-384" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Turkey-waterfront-1024x662.jpg" alt="Turkey waterfront" width="600" height="388" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<br><div style="color: #222222">There are also older districts with cobblestones, shopping and street musicians that make summer nights amazing. I also visited the ancient historical site of Ephesus, which dates back to 7,000 years ago.</div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-Street-musicians.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-380" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Istanbul-Street-musicians-1024x682.jpg" alt="Istanbul Street musicians" width="600" height="400" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<br><br><br><div style="color: #222222">Greece was a whole different experience.\r\n<div>Apart from visiting the Acropolis, I did not spend much time in Athens. Most of my time was spent on the Greek islands of Santorini and Ios.</div><br>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Greece-Acropolis-LR.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-379" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Greece-Acropolis-LR-1024x605.jpg" alt="Greece Acropolis LR" width="600" height="355" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222">Santorini is the image of Greece in the advertising world. With beautiful blue domed chapels<b>,</b> and whitewashed houses, this is island is entirely built on a ridge. Towns dot the length of the volcanic ridge, with gorgeous hotels clinging to the edges of the cliffs and offering spectacular views of the "caldera" or the bowl, dipping hundreds of feet down to the sea.</div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-383" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini-1024x682.jpg" alt="Santorini" width="600" height="400" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222">The sweet wine "Vin Santo" made in Santorini is  probably the most well known Greek wine, and touring the small wine trail and wine tasting there is very fun.</div><br>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Wine-tasting-Santorini.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-385" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Wine-tasting-Santorini-1024x467.jpg" alt="Wine tasting Santorini" width="600" height="274" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><br>\r\n<div>Viewing the sunset is a tourist ritual in Oia<b>, </b>and draws claps and cheers.</div><br>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini-Sunset-LR.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-382" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Santorini-Sunset-LR-1024x615.jpg" alt="Santorini Sunset LR" width="600" height="361" /></a></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"></div>\r\n<div></div><br>\r\n<div>The water visibility in most of these places is pretty good. So I went scuba diving on a couple of different occasions both in Turkey and Greece, discovering a variety of ocean life.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222">These countries are very worth visiting. However, visiting outside of summer is probably better, if you don\'t like crowded places.</div>\r\n<div style="color: #222222"><img src="https://ci6.googleusercontent.com/proxy/RnNZfQn2o2xpggJQqefCOervMbPIci5mujDPJnvl43kv6Rtxjyh5gHN_JKVzeU-aaGz3pePFgxfoAAtZJZNx8mveVTc-11j98EfuAJVcumUenA=s0-d-e1-ft#https://ssl.gstatic.com/ui/v1/icons/mail/images/cleardot.gif" alt="" /></div>', 'Turkey, Greece, and their waterfront life', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'turkey-greece-and-their-waterfront-life', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:16:45', '2015-05-18 17:16:45', '', 0, 'http://revamp.avenuecode.com/?p=223', 0, 'post', '', 0),
